{"source_key":"sha256-7bc7848c4bc23091c4116043a88e790b","record_index":13,"record_hash":"sha256:0b7937d0be87c1ba17395cd6b4aa17ec1789d89e4c1a8b511d5d378946829897","timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:22:35.654Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: cf8e89\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 2553\nOutput:\n# Including Turns In Agentlog\n\nThis note explores an evolution of `but-agentlog`: add a durable concept of an\nagent session turn between the project-scoped session and the captured transcript\nrecords.\n\nThe motivation is the session-association problem. The older\n[Session Association Strategy](session-association-strategy.md) is right to be\ncautious about capture-time ownership, but it treats the captured session mostly\nas one coarse object. In practice, the hook flow already gives us a more useful\nunit: every stop hook invocation is effectively a capture after an agent turn.\n\nToday `but-agentlog` deduplicates transcript records into one project session:\n\n```text\nproject session -> transcript records\n```\n\nThat stores the conversation, but it loses which newly observed records belonged\nto which capture invocation. It also loses the repository state that was true at\nthat moment. A turn layer would preserve that missing context without forcing us\nto immediately claim that the session \"belongs\" to a branch, commit, change, or\npull request.\n\n## Product Use Cases\n\nKeep this grounded in the same two use cases as the rest of the agent-session\ncapture project.\n\n### 1. Session Handoff\n\nHandoff wants enough project-scoped session context to continue work on another\nmachine or with another agent. For this use case, turns help because they add\nstructure:\n\n- the session can be reconstructed as a sequence of user/agent interactions\n- a future reader can see the repository state around each interaction\n- consumers can choose the latest turn, a specific turn, or a window of turns\n  instead of treating the whole transcript as one flat blob\n\nHandoff does not necessarily need branch association. It mostly needs readable\nconversation records, ordering, and enough environment context to orient the\nnext agent.\n\n### 2. Review Sharing\n\nReview sharing wants a GitButler web view that can show reviewers what happened\nbehind a branc\n[TRUNCATED]\n/git-meta/pull/83) added\n`MetaEdit::SetValue`, allowing typed metadata replacement inside the existing\natomic `apply_edits` path. The `but-agentlog` implementation should bump the\npinned `git-meta-lib` dependency to a revision containing that change, then use\none `apply_edits` call for transcript appends, record hash updates, turn detail\nwrites, turn summary appends, and index updates.\n\n## Environment Snapshot\n\nEach turn should capture the repository state that can help later association.\nTranscript capture is the primary operation. Environment snapshot collection is\nbest-effort: if transcript records are accepted but environment collection\nfails, still write the turn and store a failed snapshot status instead of\nfailing the whole capture.\n\nCandidate fields:\n\n- uncommitted worktree files: all tracked and untracked files with uncommitted\n  changes\n- stacks: zero, one, or many\n- branches in each stack\n- optional review unit for each branch, for example a pull request\n- commits in each branch\n- optional change id for each commit\n- files changed by each commit\n\nAlso store a compact `observed_targets` summary on the turn detail. It should\ncontain the canonical branch, review, and change keys that were indexed for this\nturn. This keeps candidate verification and future index rebuilds cheap without\nduplicating the whole environment snapshot in every reader.\n\nPlain Git mode should use the same snapshot path as GitButler mode. The\nexpectation is that the GitButler workspace/head-info APIs expose a compatible\nstack/branch shape for plain Git repositories, so `but-agentlog` should not grow\na separate plain-Git fallback model unless the shared API proves insufficient.\n\nGitButler mode is more nuanced:\n\n- there may be multiple applied branches/stacks at the same time\n- there may be zero applied branches\n- stacked branches may mean both `bottom-refactor` and `top-feature` are\n  present, while the agent session is only relevant to `top-feature`\n- two applied branches such as `my-feature` and `other-stuff` may coexist even\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:22:35.654Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}